<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-27T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-27T04:00:00-05:00" n="565" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d565">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.515/574: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-27T17:00:00+08:00">May 27, 1935—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 27—10 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>220. Department’s 135, May 21, 5 p.m. Following telegram has been
                            received from the Consulate at Tsinanfu: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“May 27, 9 a.m. Resentment towards American silver program has
                                    appeared here in mild form. Developments tending towards boycott
                                    American goods have not yet appeared and will not likely appear
                                    unless sanctioned by provincial authorities who in such matters
                                    would likely follow the advice or lead of the Nanking
                                    authorities.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <p>To Nanking and Shanghai by mail.</p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>